As discussed, modification of an antibody by any of the methods known in the art is typically designed to achieve increased binding affinity for an antigen and/or reduce immunogenicity of the antibody in the recipient. In one approach, humanized antibodies can be modified to eliminate glycosylation sites in order to increase affinity of the antibody for its cognate antigen [
Co et al., Mol Immunol 30:1361-1367 (1993
)]. Techniques such as "reshaping," "hyperchimerization," and "veneering/resurfacing" have produced humanized antibodies with greater therapeutic potential. [
Vaswami et al., Annals of Allergy, Asthma, & Immunol 81:105 (1998
